####Come watch our finalist teams present to the Mayor, City Hall, and expert judges!

---
**Case Competition Final Presentations and Reception**

Friday October 13, 10am-12pm
Vance Hall - Hoover Lounge

9:30am - Doors Open - **Capacity Limited!**
10:00am - Introduction & Welcoming Remarks
10:10am - Mayor Kenney's Remarks
10:30am to 11:20am - Finalists Teams Present
11:20am - Judges Deliberations, Vice Dean’s Thank You
11:40am - Winner Announced
12:00pm - Reception & Event End

---

###What is this?

This is a case competition for teams of Penn undergraduate, graduate, and MBA students to analyze why Amazon should locate their new headquarters in Philadelphia. 

###Why should you do this?

It's a great opportunity for Penn students to explore the intersection of business, tech, and policy, and to build city pride by creating economic prosperity for Philadelphia.

###Background Information

Amazon is looking for proposals from North American cities on where to build their second headquarters and Philadelphia is in the running as a strong candidate. The economic benefits that its current HQ have brought Seattle are tremendous; we ask for your help to bring the same to Philadelphia. See [here](https://www.amazon.com/b?ie=UTF8&node=17044620011) for Amazon's official request for proposal and relevant data. 

---

###Competition Details

**Problem Statement**: Why is Philadelphia the best city for Amazon?

In your team of 2–4, you will enter under one of these subtopics:

  1. Financial and tax incentives
  2. Talent base and employee life incentives
  3. Strategic tech-focused incentives
  4. Current and new legal incentives

Resources for teams include [subtopic guidelines](https://paper.dropbox.com/doc/Amazon-HQ2-to-Philly-Topic-Statements-VUSPSfslPKfIXMehN5Yt5?_tk=share_copylink) and [scoring rubric](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1PUpCXNmga4zWQKr15StOvPcYi3B0yVkbyNVgyVMcbBg/edit?usp=sharing). Your team can be a mix of undergrads, grads, and MBAs.

**Judging**: One finalist team will be chosen from each sub-topic by the judging professors. A single team will be chosen as the overall winner amongst the four finalist teams. 

**Final Round Deliverables**

- 7 minute presentation and 3 minute Q&A

---

###Awards

- Meet Mayor Jim Kenney during finalist presentations
- Lunch with Wharton Vice Deans Lori Rosenkopf and Howard Kaufold
- $600 in Visa gift cards and $400 in Penn Bookstore gift cards to the winning team
- Press and media recognition

**Our Sponsors**
![Images of Sponsor Logos](/content/images/2017/10/logos104.png)

Competition organized by [The Sign.al](http://www.thesign.al/) and [MUSE](http://musepenn.org/).

This competition is in no way sponsored by Amazon.

This competition is separate from the Wharton Amazon Writing Competition.

